  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "For",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The reference of this “for” is not clear at first sight. Probably the sequence of thought is that the difference of carnal and spiritual preferences is profoundly real; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "for",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the former involves death, the latter, life and peace. And it is implied that the respective persons cannot possibly therefore interchange their preferences.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to be carnally minded",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Lit. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "the mind of the flesh",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The noun rendered “mind” is cognate to the verb rendered “do mind” in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 8:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See note there. The idea includes choice, engrossment, affection towards a congenial object. See Art. IX. of the Church of England, where “the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "wisdom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " of the flesh” is the only phrase ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "not",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " admissible in a strict explanation. The E. V. here gives the sense as well as is possible, perhaps, in a brief form.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "death",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Is this legal or moral death? On the whole, we explain it of legal death, i.e. of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "doom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This idea implies the other, for the soul which is incurring the Divine Sentence cannot be ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "morally",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " “alive to God” in the sense of peace, love, and purity. But the connexion makes the idea of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "doom",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " more prominent: see ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 8:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where antagonism to the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Law",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is specified as the inevitable state of the “carnal mind.” Thus the words here mean that to have the choices and affections of unregenerate humanity is to lie under God’s sentence, and to be on the way to its infliction.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "to be spiritually minded",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Lit. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "the mind of the Spirit",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". See last note but one.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "life and peace",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] This (by analogy with the view of “death” just above) means a state of ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "acceptance",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", in its aspect (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "a",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of pardon and consequent glory; (see last note on ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 5:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ";) and (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "b",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") of secure and loving intercourse with God, with all its attendant blessings. See on ch. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 5:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—Here of course, in view of the argument of cch. 3 and 4 especially, we must note ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "how",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the being spiritually minded “is” life and peace; viz. not as the procuring cause of these blessings, which cause is the Propitiation (accepted by faith) alone; but as the state of mind in which only they can be realized and enjoyed.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
